'''Jamal Sellami''' ({{langx|ar|جَمَال السَّلَامِيّ}}; born 6 October 1970) is a Moroccan- Jordanian professional [[Association football|football manager]] and former [[Football player|player]] who currently coaches the [[Jordan national football team]].

==Playing career==
A [[midfielder]], Sellami played for several clubs, including [[Olympique Casablanca]], [[Raja Casablanca]], [[Maghreb Fez]] and [[Beşiktaş J.K.|Beşiktaş]] in Turkey.

He played for the [[Morocco national football team|Morocco national team]] and was a participant at the [[1998 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090126082232/http://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/statisticsandrecords/players/player=156752/index.html Jamal Sellami Statistics] [[FIFA]]. Retrieved 22 January 2010.</ref>

==Coaching career==
Sellami was the coach of the Moroccan club [[FUS Rabat]].

In June 2024, the [[Jordan Football Association]] announced that Sellami became the manager of the [[Jordan national football team|Jordan national team]], after [[Hussein Ammouta]], by signing a three-year contract.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.skynewsarabia.com/sport/1723987-تعيين-المغربي-جمال-السلامي-مدربا-لمنتخب-الأردن |title=تعيين المغربي جمال السلامي مدربا لمنتخب الأردن خلفا لـ عموتة |date=22 June 2024 |access-date=23 June 2024 |website=Sky News Arabia |language=ar }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.jfa.jo/news.php?id=29884&title=جمال-سلامي-مديراً-فنياً-لمنتخب-النشامى-لـ-3-سنوات |title=جمال سلامي مديراً فنياً لمنتخب النشامى لـ 3 سنوات |publisher=Jordan Football Association |language=ar |date=26 June 2024 }}</ref> He led Jordan to finish as runners-up in Group B of the [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification – AFC third round|World Cup qualification third round]], securing their first-ever participation in the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.moroccoworldnews.com/2025/06/208348/moroccan-coach-jamal-sellami-leads-jordan-to-historic-world-cup-qualification/ |title=Moroccan Coach Jamal Sellami Leads Jordan to Historic World Cup Qualification |publisher=Morocco World News |date=5 June 2025 }}</ref>

==Personal life==
After the [[2025 FIFA Arab Cup final]] loss to his native [[Morocco national football team|Morocco]], Sellami announced that he was granted [[Jordanian passport|Jordan]]ian citizenship by a royal decision from [[King Abdullah II]]. The decision was made in recognition of his significant contributions to Jordanian football, which include leading the national team to its [[2026 FIFA World Cup|first-ever World Cup]] qualification.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Daoudi |first1=Asmae |title=Jordan Grants Citizenship to Moroccan Coach Jamal Sellami |url=https://www.moroccoworldnews.com/2025/12/272443/jordan-grants-citizenship-to-moroccan-coach-jamal-sellami/ |website=moroccoworldnews.com |publisher=Morocco World News |access-date=28 December 2025 |language=English |date=18 December 2025}}</ref>

